oque complications, gothic horrors, and even the odd quiet contentment. Inspired by Defoe, Haywood, Richardson, Sterne, and Scott-authors who pioneered the English novel-the book explores the relationship between genre and gender, asking what the Enlightenment might have looked like if it had been just a little more enlightened.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPicaresque literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  a1700s art.  a1700s.  aHarlot’s Progress.  aHogarthian art.  aRake’s Progress.  aWilliam Hogarth.  abeer street.  aearly printing.  aeighteenth century art.  aeighteenth century.  aengraving.  agin lane.  ahistory of printing.  ahistory of the novel.  aliterary theory.  amoralizing art.  asatirical art.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781773850511?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781773850511423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781773850511/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles